definition.value: A peak width at inflection is the peak width calculated by the length between its two inflection points. [Allotrope]
An integration algorithm is an algorithm about integration that specifies the way an integration process is carried out. [Allotrope]
An integration algorithm type is a classification datum that classifies the integration algorithm used in an integration process. [Allotrope]
A custom information document is a document that about some labeled information entity for which limited meaning and/or context is known. [Allotrope]

Linear decadic (a,K) and Napierian attenuation coefficients (α) are equal to the corresponding absorbances divided by the optical path length through the sample, but taking into account also the effects due to scattering and luminescence. The molar absorption coefficients (decadic ε, Napierian κ) are the linear absorption coefficients divided by the amount concentration. [IUPAC]
A protein attenuation coefficient is a calculated extinction coefficient at 280 nm of a protein calculated from the number of aromatic amino acids, particularly tryptophan. [Allotrope]
A molar attenuation coefficient is an attenuation coefficient where the concentration is a molar concentration. [Allotrope]
A column void volume time is the time required for an unretained compound to traverse the column and exit. [Allotrope]
An electronic signature document is a document about some electronic signature. [Allotrope]
An account identifier is an identifier, that identifies an account in a system that people or other systems use to access it. [Allotrope]
A data system document is a document that encapsulates the information associated with some data system. [Allotrope]
A data system instance identifier is an identifier that identifies an instance of some data system. [Allotrope]
A column compartment temperature setting is a temperature setting that specifies the temperature of some column compartment. [Allotrope]
A corrected peak area is a peak area corrected for some relative response factor. [Allotrope]
A relative corrected peak area is a relative peak area that denotes the corrected area of the peak relative to some other peak or summation of peaks. . [Allotrope]

A quantitative asymmetry factor equivalent to the ratio of the time or volume from the center point of a peak to its trailing edge to that of its fronting edge at 4.4 % of the peak height. [Allotrope]

label.value: asymmetry factor squared measured at 4.4 % height

definition.value: A quantitative asymmetry factor equivalent to the square of ratio of the time or volume from the center point of a peak to its trailing edge to that of its fronting edge at 4.4 % of the peak height. [Allotrope]

label.value: asymmetry factor squared measured at 10 % height

definition.value: A quantitative asymmetry factor equivalent to the square of ratio of the time or volume from the center point of a peak to its trailing edge to that of its fronting edge at 10 % of the peak height. [Allotrope]
A quantitative asymmetry factor equivalent to the square of ratio of the time or volume from the center point of a peak to its trailing edge to that of its fronting edge. [Allotrope]

label.value: number of theoretical plates measured at 60.7 % of peak height

definition.value: The number of theoretical plates calculated by the peak width at 60.7 % of peak height (2 sigma for a gaussian peak). [Allotrope]

label.value: number of theoretical plates measured at 32.4 % of peak height

definition.value: The number of theoretical plates calculated by the peak width at 32.4 % of peak height (3 sigma for a gaussian peak). [Allotrope]

label.value: number of theoretical plates measured at 13.4 % of peak height

definition.value: The number of theoretical plates calculated by the peak width at 13.4 % of peak height (4 sigma for a gaussian peak). [Allotrope]

label.value: number of theoretical plates measured at 4.4 % of peak height

definition.value: The number of theoretical plates calculated by the peak width at 4.4 % of peak height (5 sigma for a gaussian peak). [Allotrope]
The peak width calculated at 4.4 % of its peak height. This is equivalent to 5 standard deviations of a Gaussian peak. [Allotrope]
The peak width calculated at 13.4 % of its peak height. This is equivalent to 4 standard deviations of a Gaussian peak. [Allotrope]
The peak width calculated at 32.4 % of its peak height. This is equivalent to 3 standard deviations of a Gaussian peak. [Allotrope]
The peak width calculated at 60.7 % of its peak height. This is equivalent to 2 standard deviations of a Gaussian peak. [Allotrope]

label.value: peak leading edge time at 5 % of peak height

definition.value: The time or volume from the center point of a peak to its leading edge at 5 % of the peak height. [Allotrope]
An expected retention time is a peak facet that indicates the expected retention time as specified by the data processing method. [Allotrope]
An error code is a code that indicates the error associated with the aborted state of a planned process. [Allotrope]
A chromatography peak type is a classification datum that classifies a chromatography peak by the role played by the substance it is a proxy for in the chromatographic process. [Allotrope]
A chromatography separation type is a classification datum that classifies the underlying separation process used in the chromatographic process. [Allotrope]
A log entry type is a classification datum that classifies a log entry in a log. [Allotrope]
A signature role type is a classification datum that classifies the signature role of some signature. [Allotrope]
An ASM converter is a software used to convert data into the Allotrope Simple Model format. [Allotrope]
An ADF converter is a software used to convert data into the Allotrope Data Format. [Allotrope]
An impurity type is a classification datum that classifies a peak by the impurity role played by the substance it is a proxy for in the chromatographic process. [Allotrope]
A data format conversion software is a software the converts data into a specified target format. [Allotrope]
A software name is a name of some software. [Allotrope]
An error is a description of a discrepancy between a computed, observed, or measured value or condition and the true, specified, or theoretically correct value or condition. [NCI]
A processing enabled setting is a data processing setting that allows data processing to occur. [Allotrope]

label.value: peak symmetry factor measured at 5 % peak height

definition.value: A chromatography peak facet equivalent to the ratio of the time or volume from the center point of a peak to its fronting edge divided by the entire width of the peak at 5% of the peak height. [Allotrope]

label.value: number of theoretical plates by peak width at half height (JP14)

definition.value: The number of theoretical plates calculated based on the peak width measured at half height, adjusted to use 5.55 as the square of the standard deviation in accordance with JP14. [Allotrope]
A parameter specification specific to the column compartment in the chromatography system. [Allotrope]
A calibration curve identifier is an identifier that identifies a particular calibration curve. [Allotrope]
A standard identifier is an identifier that identifies a standard being measured. [Allotrope]

A minimum peak detection slope setting is a data processing setting that defines the minimum slope of the signal (rate of change of the signal per acquisition time) at or above which the start of a peak is detected. [Allotrope]
A void volume is the volume occupied by the mobile phase between the particles in the packed section of a column. [IUPAC]
An amount of substance (datum) is a quantity facet that quantifies some amount of substance. [Allotrope]
A seal initiation temperature is the temperature at which a seal is initiated, determined by the seal's strength reaching 4 Newtons. [Allotrope]
